WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:02.980
STEPHEN CARPENTER: So we have
heard from the introductions

00:00:02.980 --> 00:00:06.820
and the backgrounds
of the people

00:00:06.820 --> 00:00:09.820
sitting around the table,
their numerous interests

00:00:09.820 --> 00:00:12.910
and numerous starting
points or ways

00:00:12.910 --> 00:00:21.290
to connect to issues of water,
of community, of access.

00:00:21.290 --> 00:00:24.400
And so the range of
disciplinary interests

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:26.200
I find quite fascinating.

00:00:26.200 --> 00:00:28.120
And in terms of
the work that I've

00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:30.310
been doing with
curriculum, it really

00:00:30.310 --> 00:00:32.350
speaks to this notion
of interdisciplinarity,

00:00:32.350 --> 00:00:36.280
and some folks use the
term transdisciplinarity.

00:00:36.280 --> 00:00:40.490
But in some ways, when we're
interested in key issues,

00:00:40.490 --> 00:00:43.450
social issues, those
disciplines go away.

00:00:43.450 --> 00:00:45.490
It's about people.

00:00:45.490 --> 00:00:48.190
It's about something beyond
science or beyond art

00:00:48.190 --> 00:00:52.810
or beyond whatever that
discipline might be.

00:00:52.810 --> 00:00:55.960
So our multiple
areas of expertise

00:00:55.960 --> 00:00:58.420
really come into play
quite nicely here.

00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:03.636
This year, not only
do I have the pleasure

00:01:03.636 --> 00:01:06.100
and the good fortune to be
able to visit three times here

00:01:06.100 --> 00:01:09.580
at MIT as a visiting artist.

00:01:09.580 --> 00:01:11.590
But I'm also a visiting
artist and visiting

00:01:11.590 --> 00:01:14.912
learner at a local
elementary school back home.

00:01:14.912 --> 00:01:16.370
And essentially,
people were asking

00:01:16.370 --> 00:01:17.630
me, what are you doing at MIT?

00:01:17.630 --> 00:01:19.630
And what are you doing
at the elementary school?

00:01:19.630 --> 00:01:22.680
And I said, I'm
doing the same thing.

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:23.620
Yeah.

00:01:23.620 --> 00:01:25.500
And the key is I'm going--

00:01:25.500 --> 00:01:28.840
I want to know at the
elementary school,

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:31.210
specifically, what they can
teach me about what I think

00:01:31.210 --> 00:01:32.740
I know about what I'm doing.

00:01:32.740 --> 00:01:34.281
And that's what
we're doing here too.

00:01:34.281 --> 00:01:37.240
I'm eager to learn about
what you can teach me

00:01:37.240 --> 00:01:39.042
about what I think I'm
doing, but also what

00:01:39.042 --> 00:01:41.500
we can teach each other, what
we can learn from each other.

00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:45.460
Quite often, in some
educational spaces,

00:01:45.460 --> 00:01:49.090
administrators,
teachers, other folks

00:01:49.090 --> 00:01:52.420
in various levels
of making decisions

00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:56.380
forget, explicitly or
otherwise, that learners

00:01:56.380 --> 00:02:00.700
bring knowledge with them to
every single learning context.

00:02:00.700 --> 00:02:03.790
So there's as much learning
going on in one direction

00:02:03.790 --> 00:02:05.510
as there are in
multiple directions.

00:02:05.510 --> 00:02:07.650
So we all have valuable
information to share.

00:02:07.650 --> 00:02:10.606
So I'm eager to have
that conversation.

00:02:10.606 --> 00:02:11.980
So it's about the
filters, right?

00:02:11.980 --> 00:02:16.660
It's about how these ceramic
water filters inspire

00:02:16.660 --> 00:02:19.780
multiple curriculum
possibilities, not just

00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:22.360
a curriculum or
instructional possibilities

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:25.250
for how do you make the filter,
and how do you use them?

00:02:25.250 --> 00:02:29.110
But there are other
ripples, pardon the pun.

00:02:29.110 --> 00:02:34.210
There are other ways that the
filters might inspire learning.

00:02:34.210 --> 00:02:37.420
For example, the
filters are designed

00:02:37.420 --> 00:02:39.880
to sit inside a plastic
water receptacle

00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:42.710
like the one you see here and
the one you saw in the video.

00:02:42.710 --> 00:02:48.160
But what if you asked artists
to create a ceramic receptacle

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:51.550
in their own style if you
gave them the specifications,

00:02:51.550 --> 00:02:53.980
and they created the
vessel in their own style?

00:02:53.980 --> 00:02:56.200
And then you could
actually have an exhibition

00:02:56.200 --> 00:02:58.950
of these receptacles.

00:02:58.950 --> 00:03:03.220
And that exhibition could
tour to different locations.

00:03:03.220 --> 00:03:06.100
And in doing so, you could
promote the exhibition.

00:03:06.100 --> 00:03:08.740
But you could also then talk
about the global water crisis.

00:03:08.740 --> 00:03:12.220
You could talk about lack
of adequate access to water.

00:03:12.220 --> 00:03:14.950
You could talk about the ways
that artists and other folks

00:03:14.950 --> 00:03:20.650
are engaging in work to
respond to these issues.

00:03:20.650 --> 00:03:25.090
And so these exhibitions went
on for a number of years.

00:03:25.090 --> 00:03:27.797
My colleagues and I were talking
about reviving this practice.

00:03:27.797 --> 00:03:30.130
The idea is if someone purchases
one of the receptacles,

00:03:30.130 --> 00:03:32.890
that money essentially is
a donation back to a water

00:03:32.890 --> 00:03:34.180
project.

00:03:34.180 --> 00:03:38.800
This is a vessel that I
created as part of that work.

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:42.310
And it's inspired by
the sanitation workers'

00:03:42.310 --> 00:03:46.090
strike in 1968, I Am a Man.

00:03:46.090 --> 00:03:48.880
And it relates in
many ways to found

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:54.300
object art, assemblage work from
some of the modernist artists.

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:59.320
That's a top of a trophy I
found at a secondhand store

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:00.710
with a guy with a little fedora.

00:04:00.710 --> 00:04:01.690
It was perfect, right?

00:04:01.690 --> 00:04:04.970
And I made these little signs.

00:04:04.970 --> 00:04:08.070
But the idea being, how
can the work of art itself

00:04:08.070 --> 00:04:11.730
function as a way to
speak out and speak back

00:04:11.730 --> 00:04:13.920
to social issues?

00:04:13.920 --> 00:04:16.290
Inspired by-- this one was
inspired by the water filters

00:04:16.290 --> 00:04:17.498
and water filter receptacles.

00:04:17.498 --> 00:04:21.779
So those links become entangled.

00:04:21.779 --> 00:04:23.910
But they also allow
for other trajectories

00:04:23.910 --> 00:04:26.196
of thinking to happen.

00:04:26.196 --> 00:04:27.570
Well, we can talk
about protests.

00:04:27.570 --> 00:04:30.130
We can talk about, well,
what is a basic human need?

00:04:30.130 --> 00:04:31.090
What is a human right?

00:04:31.090 --> 00:04:33.737
What is privilege?

00:04:33.737 --> 00:04:35.320
What do you need and
what do you want?

00:04:35.320 --> 00:04:37.780
Those are two different things.

00:04:37.780 --> 00:04:40.400
And I think those kinds of
conversations with students

00:04:40.400 --> 00:04:41.390
are quite powerful.

00:04:41.390 --> 00:04:44.240
Who has access?

00:04:44.240 --> 00:04:47.910
Who sets up the limitations?

00:04:47.910 --> 00:04:49.200
What is necessary?

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:50.424
Who takes action?

00:04:50.424 --> 00:04:51.840
These kinds of
questions, I think,

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:56.620
are central to not only
a curricula within art

00:04:56.620 --> 00:04:58.950
within education, but also
curricula within the various

00:04:58.950 --> 00:05:01.770
disciplines that are
represented around this table.

