So we have rechargeable
batteries at home

00:05:51.720 --> 00:05:53.790
that we've been very true to.

00:05:53.790 --> 00:05:55.500
We only use our
rechargeable batteries.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:58.080
That's as far as
that goes with us.

00:05:58.080 --> 00:05:59.700
And then the filter
water inside it.

00:05:59.700 --> 00:06:01.230
But water is basically good.

00:06:01.230 --> 00:06:05.370
But seeing all these
shipments of bottled water

00:06:05.370 --> 00:06:10.290
and the requests for batteries
in an island and just the

00:06:10.290 --> 00:06:16.020
waste that that will create
and that no one thinks about.

00:06:16.020 --> 00:06:19.290
And how can at least in
one corner of the world--

00:06:19.290 --> 00:06:24.220
or in this case, that island,
can we try to do something?

00:06:24.220 --> 00:06:25.860
Because I talk to my family.

00:06:25.860 --> 00:06:28.890
And they go to a river, and
that's where they bathe.

00:06:28.890 --> 00:06:31.140
And that's where they
get water to clean.

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:32.065
And clean and bathe.

00:06:32.065 --> 00:06:33.690
That's it, because
they won't drink it,

00:06:33.690 --> 00:06:36.330
because they don't know
if something died further

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:39.310
up the mountain.

00:06:39.310 --> 00:06:41.750
And they don't have
access to that.

00:06:41.750 --> 00:06:44.490
And then there's sun
everywhere, right?

00:06:44.490 --> 00:06:50.030
So just that immediate
thing, and it's

00:06:50.030 --> 00:06:53.060
called Sector Bloquera, because
at the bottom of the hill,

00:06:53.060 --> 00:06:57.260
there's a huge
hardware type of like--

00:06:57.260 --> 00:07:00.705
[SPEAKING SPANISH] just like
a lumber yard type of thing.

00:07:00.705 --> 00:07:01.830
I was going to say sawdust.

00:07:01.830 --> 00:07:03.820
I'm like, oh, I can easily get--

00:07:03.820 --> 00:07:04.340
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:04.340 --> 00:07:08.750
--I can get tons of sawdust
from the [SPEAKING SPANISH]..

00:07:11.520 --> 00:07:21.210
But yeah, the access and how, in
a limited time frame can one--

00:07:21.210 --> 00:07:25.830
as I look at that little
one right there just

00:07:25.830 --> 00:07:29.220
to do that, because--

00:07:29.220 --> 00:07:31.430
right.

00:07:31.430 --> 00:07:32.749
And that weighs nothing.

00:07:32.749 --> 00:07:34.290
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
It weighs nothing.

00:07:34.290 --> 00:07:35.810
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:07:35.810 --> 00:07:38.510
So I guess that's my of this.

00:07:38.510 --> 00:07:42.380
And then I see [INAUDIBLE],,
like [INAUDIBLE] Hartford.

00:07:42.380 --> 00:07:45.020
I'm from Hartford, so
he has Hartford roots.

00:07:45.020 --> 00:07:50.410
And Dred Scott, it's a
really exciting presentation.

00:07:50.410 --> 00:07:53.570
And he contextualizes
it really incredibly.

00:07:53.570 --> 00:07:55.880
But this really drew me
because of the immediacy

00:07:55.880 --> 00:07:57.410
of what's happening out there.

00:07:57.410 --> 00:07:58.910
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
Absolutely, yeah.

00:07:58.910 --> 00:08:07.176
Well, what we're seeing in
Puerto Rico right now is just--

00:08:07.176 --> 00:08:09.050
for me, it's beyond
words, beyond adjectives.

00:08:09.050 --> 00:08:10.800
I can't-- it's indescribable.

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:15.180
I spoke with a colleague, and
friend of mine a few days ago.

00:08:15.180 --> 00:08:16.820
His family is in Puerto Rico.

00:08:16.820 --> 00:08:18.405
And he says it's--

00:08:18.405 --> 00:08:20.780
he talked about-- before we
heard the reports in the news

00:08:20.780 --> 00:08:22.750
about the gas issues
and the water issues,

00:08:22.750 --> 00:08:25.670
he told me about both of those.

00:08:25.670 --> 00:08:30.530
I also appreciate your comment
about sending water bottles

00:08:30.530 --> 00:08:31.280
and batteries.

00:08:31.280 --> 00:08:32.654
And that just
creates more waste.

00:08:32.654 --> 00:08:33.320
It's helpful.

00:08:33.320 --> 00:08:35.659
But unless you think
about what happens

00:08:35.659 --> 00:08:39.590
beyond the life of
that material, that's

00:08:39.590 --> 00:08:41.929
being irresponsible
at some level, right?

00:08:41.929 --> 00:08:45.260
So the rechargeable, the
recyclable, the renewable

00:08:45.260 --> 00:08:46.090
is important.

00:08:46.090 --> 00:08:49.760
Yeah, these little filters
are made from the same mixture

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:50.690
as the large filters.

00:08:50.690 --> 00:08:52.100
They're just on a smaller scale.

00:08:52.100 --> 00:08:53.516
You see in the
back on that table.

00:08:53.516 --> 00:08:55.640
We made some mini
filters yesterday.

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:57.290
We still have some
clay and sawdust.

00:08:57.290 --> 00:08:58.956
We can make some more
today if you want.

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:05.240
They would need to be tested
to make sure that they

00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:07.490
have the proper flow rate.

00:09:07.490 --> 00:09:09.380
But the other thing is
we have to make sure

00:09:09.380 --> 00:09:12.710
that the water that is
there, that these filters

00:09:12.710 --> 00:09:16.700
would filter out the bad stuff
in the water that's there, OK?

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:20.930
So I'm happy to make some
small filters, if you'd

00:09:20.930 --> 00:09:23.480
like to take some with you.

00:09:23.480 --> 00:09:24.410
And you'd have to see.

00:09:24.410 --> 00:09:26.118
But you also need to
take some test kits.

00:09:26.118 --> 00:09:27.230
And I have some test kits.

00:09:27.230 --> 00:09:29.660
If I don't have them
here, I can get them.

00:09:29.660 --> 00:09:30.890
We can get them to you.

00:09:30.890 --> 00:09:33.410
But the idea is that you
need to test the water.

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:36.200
It would be equally
irresponsible to say,

00:09:36.200 --> 00:09:39.336
oh, here's something to take
with you and it doesn't work.

00:09:39.336 --> 00:09:41.210
So we have to figure
out what's in the water.

00:09:41.210 --> 00:09:44.000
And that's the basis for setting
up the filter facilities.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.460
But the idea of being
able to take some of these

00:09:46.460 --> 00:09:50.200
in your backpack
and on your carry-on

00:09:50.200 --> 00:09:54.050
and being able to distribute
it and have immediate response,

00:09:54.050 --> 00:09:55.050
that's a big deal.

00:09:55.050 --> 00:09:56.810
And so what you're
up to and the work

00:09:56.810 --> 00:10:01.100
that you're going to be
doing is very important.

00:10:01.100 --> 00:10:03.140
But these things
are fragile too.

00:10:03.140 --> 00:10:05.630
So the packing
that it would take

00:10:05.630 --> 00:10:08.370
would require taking
up some space as well.

00:10:08.370 --> 00:10:12.410
So there's always give
and take, push and pull.

00:10:12.410 --> 00:10:15.740
I was talking to
someone yesterday

00:10:15.740 --> 00:10:18.380
about a very similar
part of the conversation.

00:10:18.380 --> 00:10:23.230
And one of things we started
to do when I was at Texas A&amp;M,

00:10:23.230 --> 00:10:25.490
before I moved to Penn
State, was revolving

00:10:25.490 --> 00:10:26.896
around this very thing.

00:10:26.896 --> 00:10:28.145
And we thought, you know what.

00:10:28.145 --> 00:10:30.140
May I borrow your bottle
for just a second?

00:10:30.140 --> 00:10:33.380
This opening is about the
same size as larger bottles.

00:10:33.380 --> 00:10:36.800
I don't have one here,
so like a liter bottle.

00:10:36.800 --> 00:10:41.550
What if we turned it over,
and you cut it right here?

00:10:41.550 --> 00:10:44.345
Or you cut it just enough that
you could have a little flap,

00:10:44.345 --> 00:10:45.700
all right?

00:10:45.700 --> 00:10:50.350
And then what if we took the
same material, and instead

00:10:50.350 --> 00:10:53.320
of what some folks are
doing with making disks--

00:10:53.320 --> 00:10:58.510
they look like hockey pucks that
you can put inside PVC piping--

00:10:58.510 --> 00:11:00.315
what if we made little corks?

00:11:00.315 --> 00:11:01.690
They look like
little wine corks,

00:11:01.690 --> 00:11:03.148
but it's made out
of this material.

00:11:03.148 --> 00:11:04.495
That could fit into this bottle.

00:11:04.495 --> 00:11:05.411
So you lift the hinge.

00:11:05.411 --> 00:11:06.760
You put the cork down there.

00:11:06.760 --> 00:11:10.450
And then we have our own
little portable receptacle.

00:11:10.450 --> 00:11:13.772
So it would take this
bottle that then gets

00:11:13.772 --> 00:11:14.980
discarded that creates waste.

00:11:14.980 --> 00:11:20.007
Maybe it becomes a
repurposed individual?

00:11:20.007 --> 00:11:21.340
Yeah, you're just creating cork.

00:11:21.340 --> 00:11:24.820
How many wine corks could
you take in your backpack?

00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:26.740
Hundreds, right?

00:11:26.740 --> 00:11:29.860
So it's that notion of scale
and responsibility and access

00:11:29.860 --> 00:11:30.670
and immediacy.

00:11:30.670 --> 00:11:34.450
Maybe after a couple
of weeks or maybe

00:11:34.450 --> 00:11:38.580
in this case, unfortunately,
a couple of months,

00:11:38.580 --> 00:11:40.182
there would not be that need.

00:11:40.182 --> 00:11:42.140
And you'd have ways to
deal with the recycling.

00:11:42.140 --> 00:11:43.900
But anyway, what
you're talking about

00:11:43.900 --> 00:11:48.410
is a very important issue
and set of concerns.

00:11:48.410 --> 00:11:52.810
I first became familiar with
the term "creative disruption"

00:11:52.810 --> 00:11:57.580
from David Darts, who
is an art educator,

00:11:57.580 --> 00:12:02.200
and his doctoral
dissertation and work looking

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:06.520
at the practice of culture
jamming, which grows out

00:12:06.520 --> 00:12:11.350
of an entire practice
of responding

00:12:11.350 --> 00:12:15.500
to capitalism and advertising.

00:12:15.500 --> 00:12:19.990
So David looked at this idea
of visual culture jamming,

00:12:19.990 --> 00:12:21.480
where you add--

00:12:21.480 --> 00:12:23.950
instead of looking at
culture-specific broadly--

00:12:23.950 --> 00:12:28.240
visual culture, more
specifically, and the way one

00:12:28.240 --> 00:12:32.800
might look at the visual
components of a culture

00:12:32.800 --> 00:12:34.690
differently through
some sort of what

00:12:34.690 --> 00:12:36.880
he called creative disruption.

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:41.200
Creative meaning,
his sense, coming

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:44.100
from an artistic or cultural
production perspective,

00:12:44.100 --> 00:12:47.380
but yeah, you can be disruptive.

00:12:49.930 --> 00:12:52.600
One might argue, you know, any
kind of disruption is creative.

00:12:52.600 --> 00:12:54.670
But certainly, the
creative in this sense

00:12:54.670 --> 00:12:59.570
comes from a more generic
notion of artistic or cultural

00:12:59.570 --> 00:13:00.070
production.

