Harvard Business
School, they've been

00:13:16.150 --> 00:13:18.850
teaching courses in
creative destruction

00:13:18.850 --> 00:13:21.190
as a strategy for
entrepreneurship.

00:13:21.190 --> 00:13:25.720
So if you want to take
on the big companies,

00:13:25.720 --> 00:13:31.840
you need to do something that
disrupts the whole logic of how

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:34.792
whatever that service or product
is is organized and presented.

00:13:34.792 --> 00:13:36.250
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
Part of the work

00:13:36.250 --> 00:13:39.550
that I do at my
current university

00:13:39.550 --> 00:13:41.650
and previous universities
in art education

00:13:41.650 --> 00:13:50.320
is to prepare teachers of
art, but even K-12 teachers.

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:52.670
And so with that
preparation, there

00:13:52.670 --> 00:13:58.000
are methods courses or
curriculum development courses

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:01.180
that essentially are structured
to respond in many ways

00:14:01.180 --> 00:14:04.990
to very specific
skills or content.

00:14:04.990 --> 00:14:09.400
And that's all fine
and good, except, what

00:14:09.400 --> 00:14:11.680
I find more interesting
are the questions

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:15.340
that emerge that can be
center points for curriculum.

00:14:15.340 --> 00:14:18.040
So instead of thinking
of curriculum development

00:14:18.040 --> 00:14:20.740
and management, it's the idea
of theorizing curriculum.

00:14:20.740 --> 00:14:28.030
So spinning it around in
terms of the questioning, most

00:14:28.030 --> 00:14:32.380
teacher preparation programs
that I'm familiar with,

00:14:32.380 --> 00:14:34.240
because there are
these standards

00:14:34.240 --> 00:14:37.480
and points for
accreditation, students

00:14:37.480 --> 00:14:40.360
must meet specific responses.

00:14:40.360 --> 00:14:44.800
And they're pretty
rigid, those curricula.

00:14:44.800 --> 00:14:49.210
But I think that there are
ways to play in and around.

00:14:49.210 --> 00:14:51.860
I've worked this
way for a while.

00:14:51.860 --> 00:14:56.620
Around, by still responding
to those expectations

00:14:56.620 --> 00:14:58.750
for certification,
but at the same time,

00:14:58.750 --> 00:15:00.700
open it up so that
teachers become

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:03.790
knowledgeable and prepared
and have experience

00:15:03.790 --> 00:15:10.596
to have an ongoing engagement
with learning and developing

00:15:10.596 --> 00:15:12.220
interesting and
exciting curricula that

00:15:12.220 --> 00:15:13.610
responds to social practices.

00:15:13.610 --> 00:15:14.110
For

00:15:14.110 --> 00:15:23.790
Example, the idea of focusing
on a theme or a concept

00:15:23.790 --> 00:15:29.780
or a question, rather than on
a specific outcome or skill.

00:15:29.780 --> 00:15:36.150
Just making that shift is a big
challenge for a lot of teacher

00:15:36.150 --> 00:15:38.490
preparation programs,
because what you're doing

00:15:38.490 --> 00:15:41.192
is you're essentially saying,
the predetermined content

00:15:41.192 --> 00:15:42.900
that we have and the
predetermined skills

00:15:42.900 --> 00:15:46.530
that we have is not all
there is to our discipline,

00:15:46.530 --> 00:15:47.980
that there could be more to it.

00:15:47.980 --> 00:15:53.970
And it also suggests that it's
not really the idea of learning

00:15:53.970 --> 00:15:55.330
that's important in education.

00:15:55.330 --> 00:15:57.750
It's about teaching content.

00:15:57.750 --> 00:16:00.480
So I like to turn also
the shift from teaching

00:16:00.480 --> 00:16:04.670
to learning, to making the
project about learning.

00:16:04.670 --> 00:16:07.080
And so this is how I'm going
about it myself, Larry,

00:16:07.080 --> 00:16:09.930
working with undergrads
and grad students

00:16:09.930 --> 00:16:13.240
to put questions at the
center of their curriculum.

00:16:13.240 --> 00:16:16.460
So it becomes an
inquiry-based approach.

00:16:16.460 --> 00:16:20.070
Or it becomes a
thematic approach.

00:16:20.070 --> 00:16:22.470
And often, it's inspired
by social issues.

00:16:22.470 --> 00:16:24.420
I can show you an
example or two,

00:16:24.420 --> 00:16:27.310
if you'd like, and
specifically to water.

00:16:27.310 --> 00:16:32.020
So one of the things that
I've enjoyed doing is using--

00:16:32.020 --> 00:16:35.850
we've had a back and
forth, Larry, about access

00:16:35.850 --> 00:16:37.800
to education in broad spaces.

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:39.520
Online is one way
that that happens.

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:42.390
So MindMeister is
a free application.

00:16:42.390 --> 00:16:45.060
And so my early work in
curriculum theorizing

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:50.760
and development looked
at spatial hypertext.

00:16:50.760 --> 00:16:53.960
So what if you took
a concept like--

00:16:53.960 --> 00:16:54.960
and more than a concept.

00:16:54.960 --> 00:16:58.410
I mean, water is a
broad idea, a big--

00:16:58.410 --> 00:17:01.800
so what if we put water
at the center here?

00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:05.910
And what I did was, I said,
look, at a group of students,

00:17:05.910 --> 00:17:08.130
we said, if we put water
at the center, what

00:17:08.130 --> 00:17:12.720
are the ideas and questions and
concepts that emerge from just

00:17:12.720 --> 00:17:14.980
us thinking about water?

00:17:14.980 --> 00:17:19.579
So there might be technology
concerns and issues

00:17:19.579 --> 00:17:21.130
related to pollution.

00:17:21.130 --> 00:17:26.150
There are contemporary artists
who are looking at and thinking

00:17:26.150 --> 00:17:28.195
about water.

00:17:28.195 --> 00:17:33.260
There's information then at
the next level that relates

00:17:33.260 --> 00:17:36.600
to our understandings of water.

00:17:36.600 --> 00:17:41.660
And so what you're seeing
here is an interconnected web

00:17:41.660 --> 00:17:45.870
of information inspired by
the simple notion of water.

00:17:45.870 --> 00:17:47.289
What if you as a teacher--

00:17:47.289 --> 00:17:49.080
you can be a teacher,
you can be an artist,

00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:50.510
you can be whatever--

00:17:50.510 --> 00:17:52.100
what does water
make you think of?

00:17:52.100 --> 00:17:53.090
What questions emerge?

00:17:53.090 --> 00:17:56.070
What do you know about water?

00:17:56.070 --> 00:17:58.410
What are you curious
about about water?

00:17:58.410 --> 00:18:01.562
If you start curriculum
in that place--

00:18:01.562 --> 00:18:02.270
what do you know?

00:18:02.270 --> 00:18:03.103
What don't you know?

00:18:03.103 --> 00:18:04.880
What would be
interesting to know?

00:18:04.880 --> 00:18:09.140
And you go off in these
various dimensions.

00:18:09.140 --> 00:18:12.110
And you start to
learn along the way.

00:18:12.110 --> 00:18:13.850
And you're not doing
it by yourself.

00:18:13.850 --> 00:18:16.160
You're learning with
a group of people.

00:18:16.160 --> 00:18:18.950
So everyone in class
has access to this web.

00:18:18.950 --> 00:18:20.420
Everyone in class,
over the series

00:18:20.420 --> 00:18:21.878
of days that we're
working on this,

00:18:21.878 --> 00:18:24.830
can see how it continues
to be populated.

00:18:24.830 --> 00:18:27.740
And we all have access to
everybody else's information.

00:18:27.740 --> 00:18:30.200
This is a curriculum
right here of water

00:18:30.200 --> 00:18:36.740
that could be navigated,
that could be--

00:18:36.740 --> 00:18:39.020
and again, I'm not showing
you all of the details.

00:18:39.020 --> 00:18:41.046
But you could select
certain components of it,

00:18:41.046 --> 00:18:42.170
highlight those components.

00:18:42.170 --> 00:18:43.250
There might be
some key questions.

00:18:43.250 --> 00:18:44.624
You might like
some of the things

00:18:44.624 --> 00:18:46.015
that one person looked at.

00:18:46.015 --> 00:18:48.140
All right, so here are some
issues about pollution,

00:18:48.140 --> 00:18:50.420
sanitation in civilizations.

00:18:50.420 --> 00:18:53.360
This piece also allows
us to put embedded video

00:18:53.360 --> 00:18:54.600
and other content.

00:18:54.600 --> 00:18:58.850
So the idea would be, if
the preparation of teachers

00:18:58.850 --> 00:19:02.300
or the work that teachers do
as they prepare to be certified

00:19:02.300 --> 00:19:07.570
and licensed moves away, in
my view, from only focusing

00:19:07.570 --> 00:19:11.140
on discipline content,
only on discipline skills,

00:19:11.140 --> 00:19:15.700
but privileges the questioning
and the nurturing of inquiry

00:19:15.700 --> 00:19:17.952
and learning, I
think what we have is

00:19:17.952 --> 00:19:19.285
we have a different sensibility.

00:19:19.285 --> 00:19:21.070
You have teachers
who aren't limited

00:19:21.070 --> 00:19:23.410
by their own disciplines
and are seeking ways

00:19:23.410 --> 00:19:24.820
to make those connections.

00:19:24.820 --> 00:19:27.790
And in doing that,
a curriculum that

00:19:27.790 --> 00:19:30.040
comes from this
mode of development

00:19:30.040 --> 00:19:33.310
can then respond to any state
or local standards of learning,

00:19:33.310 --> 00:19:36.520
any national
curriculum concerns.

00:19:36.520 --> 00:19:38.800
The example I want to show you--

00:19:38.800 --> 00:19:42.550
you ever been to an
elementary art exhibit,

00:19:42.550 --> 00:19:44.990
and you see all of the
images look very similar?

00:19:44.990 --> 00:19:47.860
You see all the paintings
and the drawings, whatever.

00:19:47.860 --> 00:19:49.810
Rarely, do we see art criticism.

00:19:49.810 --> 00:19:51.910
Rarely, do you see
young children's art

00:19:51.910 --> 00:19:53.955
historical papers on display.

00:19:53.955 --> 00:19:55.330
It happens every
once in a while.

00:19:55.330 --> 00:20:00.040
This is a water filter display
at the Chesterfield County

00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:01.180
Exhibition.

00:20:01.180 --> 00:20:02.560
So this is just one teacher.

00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:03.610
Sean Collins did this.

00:20:03.610 --> 00:20:06.880
And so he used the water filters
as part of his curriculum

00:20:06.880 --> 00:20:10.420
but also as part of
the art exhibition.

00:20:10.420 --> 00:20:12.790
He got comments from
teachers, like, wow, what?

00:20:12.790 --> 00:20:14.572
How does this-- art?

00:20:14.572 --> 00:20:16.030
This is part of
your art curricula?

00:20:16.030 --> 00:20:17.149
Well, yeah, why not?

00:20:17.149 --> 00:20:18.190
This is what we're doing.

00:20:18.190 --> 00:20:20.890
And he linked it to Greek vases.

00:20:20.890 --> 00:20:23.830
And he linked it to
expressionist painting.

00:20:23.830 --> 00:20:26.360
He linked it to all sorts
of other components.

00:20:26.360 --> 00:20:31.300
But by making the art curriculum
or the space in which an artist

00:20:31.300 --> 00:20:34.960
might think inclusive of
appropriate technology

00:20:34.960 --> 00:20:37.707
and social issues and
social responsibility,

00:20:37.707 --> 00:20:39.040
that's a disruption right there.

00:20:39.040 --> 00:20:40.330
So can elementary kids do it?

00:20:40.330 --> 00:20:41.800
Absolutely, they can.

00:20:41.800 --> 00:20:44.440
This is a page from
the Reservoir Studio,

00:20:44.440 --> 00:20:46.510
including names of
the art teachers

00:20:46.510 --> 00:20:49.690
who have agreed to work
with me or found interest

00:20:49.690 --> 00:20:53.590
or that have invited me to
do water filter performances

00:20:53.590 --> 00:20:55.810
but also work on
curricula with them.

00:20:55.810 --> 00:20:56.990
And this list keeps growing.

00:20:56.990 --> 00:20:57.940
I haven't updated it yet.

00:20:57.940 --> 00:21:00.065
But I have several others
who have been interested.

00:21:00.065 --> 00:21:03.181
Here's a person who came to a
curriculum conference, Denise

00:21:03.181 --> 00:21:03.680
Gordon.

00:21:03.680 --> 00:21:06.120
She was a science
educator in Texas.

00:21:06.120 --> 00:21:08.410
She came to this curriculum
and pedagogy conference.

00:21:08.410 --> 00:21:10.930
And instead of
presenting a paper

00:21:10.930 --> 00:21:14.500
on the water filters, my
colleague, my mentor Richard

00:21:14.500 --> 00:21:18.280
Wukich and I, we set up a water
filter production facility.

00:21:18.280 --> 00:21:22.950
And we made filters as our
conference presentation.

00:21:22.950 --> 00:21:25.240
And so people coming in
expecting to see a paper

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:28.240
presented, they helped
me sift sawdust.

00:21:28.240 --> 00:21:30.195
And [CHUCKLES] we
made the filters.

00:21:30.195 --> 00:21:32.890
The reason I'm telling you that
is because Denise Gordon showed

00:21:32.890 --> 00:21:35.039
up to that presentation.

00:21:35.039 --> 00:21:36.580
And she said, I am
a science teacher,

00:21:36.580 --> 00:21:38.800
but I think in these
interdisciplinary ways.

00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:41.180
And I like these experiential,
hands-on approaches.

00:21:41.180 --> 00:21:45.270
And so I sent her four
mini-filters at her request,

00:21:45.270 --> 00:21:49.390
two that had silver embedded
in them and two that did not.

00:21:49.390 --> 00:21:53.110
And her advanced
science students,

00:21:53.110 --> 00:21:56.500
middle school students, did
tests on those water filters.

00:21:56.500 --> 00:21:58.720
They tested the water
from two local sources.

00:21:58.720 --> 00:22:01.690
They did research on the
production of the filters.

00:22:01.690 --> 00:22:03.160
And they set up--

00:22:03.160 --> 00:22:04.780
they found other
commercial filters,

00:22:04.780 --> 00:22:06.430
and they ran the results.

00:22:06.430 --> 00:22:08.770
And they found that
these little filters

00:22:08.770 --> 00:22:12.266
worked as well or better than
those commercial filters on two

00:22:12.266 --> 00:22:13.390
different sources of water.

00:22:13.390 --> 00:22:16.030
One was, I think,
the local river.

00:22:16.030 --> 00:22:18.820
And the other was some
other sewage space.

00:22:18.820 --> 00:22:21.640
But my point is that she
empowered her students

00:22:21.640 --> 00:22:25.207
to take control and
to lead the inquiry.

00:22:25.207 --> 00:22:26.290
And this is middle school.

00:22:26.290 --> 00:22:28.150
So can middle school
students think in these ways

00:22:28.150 --> 00:22:30.775
and consider their place in the
world and their responsibility?

00:22:30.775 --> 00:22:31.420
Absolutely.

00:22:31.420 --> 00:22:34.812
And again, these are just
two of many possible ways

00:22:34.812 --> 00:22:35.770
that this might happen.

00:22:35.770 --> 00:22:39.640
But just responding
specifically to that question.

00:22:39.640 --> 00:22:42.700
AUDIENCE: How do we
place for the disruptive

00:22:42.700 --> 00:22:45.030
way of doing things
and incremental way

00:22:45.030 --> 00:22:46.530
of doing that thing?

00:22:46.530 --> 00:22:50.920
Probably what is existing,
taking it ahead and improving

00:22:50.920 --> 00:22:55.000
on it may be quite incremented
and disruptive where

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:57.700
you put a full stop and
start with something new.

00:22:57.700 --> 00:22:59.770
In fact, ceramic
filter itself, I

00:22:59.770 --> 00:23:01.540
don't know whether to
call it disruptive,

00:23:01.540 --> 00:23:03.370
because a filter existed.

00:23:03.370 --> 00:23:06.700
And it was modified
in some ways.

00:23:06.700 --> 00:23:09.150
So I'm really confused
about these definitions

00:23:09.150 --> 00:23:10.990
about disruptive, incremental.

00:23:10.990 --> 00:23:12.280
What is it?

00:23:12.280 --> 00:23:14.410
And how do you go
back, especially

00:23:14.410 --> 00:23:17.980
in terms of disasters,
where I think the need is

00:23:17.980 --> 00:23:19.672
to go back to basics?

00:23:19.672 --> 00:23:21.880
STEPHEN CARPENTER: For me,
disruption is incremental.

00:23:21.880 --> 00:23:22.520
It's a process.

00:23:22.520 --> 00:23:25.810
It's a verb in my thinking.

00:23:25.810 --> 00:23:29.432
Certainly one can disrupt
with a specific action.

00:23:29.432 --> 00:23:31.640
And it seems like it's only
happening in that moment.

00:23:31.640 --> 00:23:34.980
But we can think more broadly
that once that moment happens,

00:23:34.980 --> 00:23:38.050
there are continuing
echoes from that.

00:23:38.050 --> 00:23:42.160
So I think it's also
site-specific too,

00:23:42.160 --> 00:23:45.910
the degree of incremental change
or disruption that happens.

00:23:45.910 --> 00:23:46.840
But I don't--

00:23:46.840 --> 00:23:49.780
I'm not thinking about
disruption, necessarily,

00:23:49.780 --> 00:23:51.850
as one specific moment.

00:23:51.850 --> 00:23:57.910
I think of it in a longer term,
in a moving, time-based way.

00:23:57.910 --> 00:23:59.410
So that's one part
of your question.

00:23:59.410 --> 00:24:01.493
I think the second part
had to do with the filters

00:24:01.493 --> 00:24:03.940
and seeing them as disruptive.

00:24:03.940 --> 00:24:07.270
And certainly, for folks who
didn't have adequate access

00:24:07.270 --> 00:24:10.960
to clean water and now
they might have access,

00:24:10.960 --> 00:24:13.900
the filters have disrupted
that previous narrative

00:24:13.900 --> 00:24:18.150
of inaccessibility,
and have disrupted

00:24:18.150 --> 00:24:21.340
a longstanding-- a
generational experience

00:24:21.340 --> 00:24:26.290
with being sick
and having disease.

00:24:26.290 --> 00:24:32.280
So it's disrupting that health
issue and that human issue.

00:24:32.280 --> 00:24:33.380
And so there's that.

00:24:33.380 --> 00:24:35.160
And then going back
to basic, absolutely.

00:24:35.160 --> 00:24:36.890
I mean, you do what
you need to do.

00:24:36.890 --> 00:24:40.580
And certainly, the
water's coming down.

00:24:40.580 --> 00:24:42.860
Let's get some plastic
and collect the water.

00:24:42.860 --> 00:24:47.450
I mean, that seems like the
most appropriate technology

00:24:47.450 --> 00:24:50.480
that we've talked about today.

00:24:50.480 --> 00:24:53.450
I think your examples
are right on.

00:24:53.450 --> 00:24:55.644
And I hope it clarified
a little bit how

00:24:55.644 --> 00:24:57.560
I'm thinking about
disruption, not as an idea.

00:24:57.560 --> 00:25:00.050
I didn't clarify-- disruption
for me is not a moment.

00:25:00.050 --> 00:25:01.020
But it's an ongoing--

00:25:01.020 --> 00:25:02.145
AUDIENCE: It's a continuum.

00:25:02.145 --> 00:25:04.280
STEPHEN CARPENTER: It's
a continuum, absolutely.

00:25:04.280 --> 00:25:04.780
Yeah.

00:25:04.780 --> 00:25:05.544
And it's variable.

00:25:05.544 --> 00:25:06.710
AUDIENCE: It was my job too.

00:25:06.710 --> 00:25:09.360
I mean, it's a job
for us to do that.

00:25:09.360 --> 00:25:12.590
So even though it's
disruptive or not disruptive,

00:25:12.590 --> 00:25:15.617
my job is to provide clean
water to people out there.

00:25:15.617 --> 00:25:16.700
And that's what I'm doing.

00:25:16.700 --> 00:25:19.280
[CHUCKLES] So whether
it is disruptive or not,

00:25:19.280 --> 00:25:20.360
it's that simple.

00:25:20.360 --> 00:25:21.901
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
Well, yeah, it is.

00:25:21.901 --> 00:25:24.470
Yeah, yeah, and I
think sometimes I

00:25:24.470 --> 00:25:26.895
like to be a bit more dramatic,
maybe, than necessary.

00:25:26.895 --> 00:25:28.340
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:28.340 --> 00:25:32.480
And to think more
broadly or differently,

00:25:32.480 --> 00:25:34.810
folks didn't have the water.

00:25:34.810 --> 00:25:36.500
And you allow water
to be available.

00:25:36.500 --> 00:25:38.749
You disrupted their
lack of access, so--

00:25:38.749 --> 00:25:40.040
AUDIENCE: I think I did my job.

00:25:40.040 --> 00:25:40.540
[CHUCKLES]

00:25:40.540 --> 00:25:42.370
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
You did your job.

